
Pimp My Search was a novelty website to create a Google lookalike webpage, replacing the word "Google" with a word or phrase of the user's choice.[tpl]cite web | author=Bennett, Geoffrey | title=Has Google Finally Met Its Match? | url=http://www.npr.org/blogs/newsandviews/2008/05/has_google_finally_met_its_mat.html | work=NPR | publisher= | date=2008-05-14 | accessdate=2009-05-21[/tpl][tpl]cite web | author=Gill, Ronnie | title=Pimpmysearch.com offers a Google-like Web site | url=http://www.newsday.com/services/newspaper/printedition/monday/partii/ny-lshow5833924sep08a,0,4325335.story | work=Newsday | publisher= | date=2008-09-08 | accessdate=2009-05-21[/tpl] It is a non-commercial website and is not connected to Google, Inc.[tpl]Fact|date=May 2009[/tpl] Pimp My Search was started in 2006, but became popular only in 2008 after featured in many media websites and YouTube videos.[tpl]Fact|date=May 2009[/tpl] The site was closed down later in 2009, citing a dispute over 'trademark issues'.

==Controversies with Google==

In February 2009, Pimp my Search ended Google search facilities and a posted a message that read: "Because of Trademark issues Google is no longer allowing searches from us...".http://www.pimpmysearch.com/problem.php?q=  Retrieved on 2009-05-25. Currently, the site remains closed, with the following message displayed: "Because of Trademark issues Pimp my Search is closed for ever.http://www.pimpmysearch.com  Retrieved on 2009-05-25.

